  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published by Peter Lang Verlag in 2023, Luis Mart\u00ednez-Fern\u00e1ndez's <em>When the World Turned Upside Down</em> has established its most tangible footprint as a pedagogical resource, appearing in multiple teaching contexts and accumulating early scholarly citations that signal a slowly growing presence in academic discourse on geopolitics, expansionism, and contemporary world history.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's strongest documented impact lies in its pedagogical reach. The author presented the work at a UCF Celebrates the Arts event in April 2023, and the volume has been discussed across at least two YouTube channels\u2014including one dedicated to history education\u2014indicating that it is finding an audience among students and general readers interested in the turbulent events of 2019\u20132022. Library holdings across three institutions further confirm that the book has been acquired as a teaching and reference resource, a meaningful signal for a recently published scholarly title in the humanities.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Scholarly citation activity, while modest at three recorded citations, offers an early and geographically varied reception. Citing works originate from institutions in the United States and Poland, and appear in venues ranging from the <em>Humboldt Journal of Social Relations</em> to a volume in the <em>Second Language Learning and Teaching</em> series. The thematic diversity of these citing works\u2014spanning Indigenous genocide studies, travel literature, and social relations\u2014suggests that Mart\u00ednez-Fern\u00e1ndez's framing of recent global upheaval resonates across disciplinary boundaries, even if the citation base remains nascent. The book's citation percentile of approximately 23 reflects its early stage of circulation rather than limited relevance.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Conceptually, the volume is anchored in expansionism, geopolitics, and militarism, with particular attention to China and world-historical context. This thematic positioning places it at a productive intersection of political science, economic history, and media studies\u2014fields actively grappling with the seismic shifts of the early 2020s. The book's engagement with these urgent questions gives it a strong basis for continued uptake as scholars and educators increasingly seek synthetic accounts of that period.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, <em>When the World Turned Upside Down</em> is best characterized at this stage as a pedagogical anchor with emerging scholarly uptake. Its presence in classrooms and public educational forums is its clearest contribution so far, and the disciplinary breadth of its early citers suggests that wider scholarly engagement may develop as the field consolidates its understanding of the 2019\u20132022 conjuncture. Given its recent publication date, the trajectory remains open and bears watching.</p>",
